fields.description: Start with the construction material in portrait mode and you get a regular one. Landscape mode gives you what we used to call a "funny" one with a pointed tail. This gift includes several much more special designs and the material to make them too.
Are you age six or older? Do you like building things? If so, you may find yourself magnetically attracted to this gift.

Another slightly used item -- I'm downsizing before retirement, alright? It comes in 62 small pieces, and doesn't take up near as much space as the original, nor does it fly there. Select this gift and make a Discovery.
"Seeing is believing" they say, but they're wrong. The eye can be fooled. If you would you like to try fifty different ways to do that, select this gift.
If those are all protons it's a product of a nuclear fusion cycle and not dangerous at all. They might be just as puzzling to put together though. Ages 8 and up.
The receiver of this gift might want to get into a contest with the receiver of Gift 2. If that doesn't fly you'll at least have twenty different models.
Rub a dub, dub, four rings in a tub; With an anchor too, so it won't get away from you! But then this probably better for a little one who can't read this yet and who likes bath toys. (6+ months).
"Amaze your family and friends!" it says. And if you learn the things that use these common things you might just be able to do that. They'll be wondering "How did you do that?"
Is it art? Is it science? Is it both? Art does have a method behind it and Science does have its beauty. I don't think you'll be needing any crystal ball to have some fun growing these.
Remember that play-intended soft stuff? You can stuff some of it in here, push on the lever, and extrude a lot of different shapes. This might be something your 3+ year old could enjoy.
Jacob may have to help me out here, but this may be the "ONE" game he and I played with Aunt Mary Piatt. Or was that Skip Bo? In any case, we played it in English, not Spanish.
If you are of an experimental frame of mind, and like science, you may like this. It will show you how to use any number of things you'd find around the house, including the kitchen sink!

Hmm... something tells me I may have given a version of this away before, even though this one claims to be the original. Ages five and up for three or more players who know left from right and can center on the game.
Meant to help with those glassy things that help make pictures this little kit may be able to remove some of the stuff that settles on other items also. You can huff and puff and blow it all away!
Click! Well, no images are saved, but this thing has 7 activities, sounds and lights to interest your 6+ month old. Maybe a young-un you know would like to learn the things it can do.
You could forget this game but I don't think you're supposed to. It has nine little cubes for a game for two or more players from ages 8 to adult.
How convincing can you be when you aren't really telling the truth? That's not necessarily a good trait to have in life, but it could help in this game. Two or more players, ages 10 and up.

I think one of you already received this but left it behind one year and now I don't know who. Perhaps he or she was just tired of having their brain teased. Ages 7 to adult with a bunch of small pieces.
Ooooh! More experiments with everyday objects. This set in a field of interest to me. In fact, some of them may be done in a field.
Think of something crunchy... that you know too much about. Would you shout it out for all to hear? If so you might enjoy this gift. Three to eight players ages 10 and up.
Who thinks like you? Anyone? Hopefully you'll find someone who does for this game. The box says it's for three to eight players ages 12 and up.

Can you solve this? From outside the container I can't tell much about it but it seems to be a mystery game for two or more players ages 8 and up. I have a feeling that playing the Christmas Concentration game may help though. (If I can get it to work.)
Hey Bud! Got your ears on? With these you can use your mouth too.
To put a little light on the subject, or maybe a lot depending on how you use it. Let it hang around someplace or store it on your refrigerator if you want to know where it is. Batteries included.
People don't generally like to be pressured but, for some things, having too little is as bad as having too much. This gift may help you discern which is which.
Oooh! Spooky! This gift may seem to go more with Halloween than Christmas but I always enjoyed these kinds of things. Some of the ones here are quite famous.
With the titular character named after a file drawer you may enjoy reading the original version of this story and four if its sequels.
Do you like cats? You might want to find some. Do you hate cats? You might want to know where they are hiding. This will give you a chance to practice in either case.
Questions and answers, questions and answers, not necessarily in that order. Three or more players ages 12 and up.

It may float like a butterfly and I suppose if you tried hard enough it could sting like a bee, but it has nothing to do with Muhammad Ali! Somebody gave it to me knowing that I like science-related toys and magical levitation. Ages 5 to 105! Slightly used, but still quite usable.
More questions and answers. These may come in a more conventional order and require you to remember names -- like that of a certain New York Jets quarterback. Two or more players, ages 12 and up.
If you were old enough back in the 1970's and 80's you might have a lot of this trivia in your memory. For the rest, it's history!
"puzzlE me this, batman!" no, that's not it. You don't imagine youRself to be on the Batman tv show but a different cHaracter whiLe sOlving these Kases. Can you gueSs who?
Perhaps you like a more modern ambiance to your crime solving investigations than is offered by Gift 33. If so, you might want to try this one.

Hmm... I wonder if this will give away any of the ones in Gift 9. This one offers both more and less than Gift 9 though. You have to supply your own set of common little things but you get more things to do with them.

Somehow I associate this with Grandpa O'Brien and Aunt Nor. Maybe I got it as a Christmas gift from them. Maybe I played it first with one of them. Maybe it's why, years later, I did well in Geometry: I could flip those triangles around in my head!
Draw it, erase it. Draw it, erase it. It's not like one of those magic slates we used to have, but it's a whole lot easier to use than an Etch-A-Sketch! Children ages 3 and up.

We played Skip Bo. The match was so historic, it was chronicled in the local newspaper
No Sh#&!

fields.memory: I can only vaguely recall Christmas at Grandpa's and all I remember is that is was loud and crowded.

At the moment, my earliest Christmas memory is being at grandpa's, receiving a little toy piano, sitting on a couch with cousin Kathy, who also got a piano. As I recall, we were playing them and she reached over and ripped a page from my music book that came with the piano. I don't remember what happened after that. I find it odd that this scene is what I remember.

I think my earliest Christmas memory was at Grampa's house. I saw a toy gas station there and I just knew it must be mine. I kept waiting and waiting for Grampa to call my name. I even helped him along: "J-I-M-M-Y" in case he didn't know how to spell it.

At Grandpa's, I remember the tree in the corner that later became occupied by the first television in our family.  I remember Uncle Red, still a teenager I think, coming and going with his friend Norey.  I remember the children''s table in the little room off the dining room that we considered to be Aunt Nelly's room.  Peggy, our pretty older cousin I found so glamorous. 
 And Aunt Nelly seated in a rocking chair and usually asleep was somehow central to the occasion.  And the hand sewn clothing from mom and Aunt Nor.  How did they find the time?  At home, I remember Dad hanging big and probably dangerous glass lights on the tree, the glass decorations from war time we had to handle carefully, the tinsel that we called icicles, and the impossible effort to stay awake to listen for Santa sounds.  I will never forget that coffee cake baking for us while we opened gifts.
One of my fondest Christmas memories was the time spent every Christmas while I was at home, making dozens of cookies with my mom while we played Christmas music and talked.
I never saw it happen but I remember that Santa Claus came down an old register in the kitchen ceiling. We didn't have a fireplace for him to use.

One year, when I was stationed at New Buffalo, it was looking like it was going to be a brown Christmas -- no snow anywhere, just dead brown grass.  I remember coming out the front doors of the church after Midnight Mass to the most beautiful white fluffy snowflakes!  It was just like a movie!
Waiting upstairs on Christmas morning,  waiting to be called down to use bathroom,  and trying to sneak a peek at tree when it was my turn.
The living room, so dark and mysterious as we came down for early mass.  Dad at the kitchen stove,  Mom's coffee cake and a doll I named Pat.
Doing extra chores to earn money to buy Christmas gifts.

I remember staring out the windows Christmas eve looking for Rudolphs red nose up in the sky. With planes coming and going from the airport we were convinced any red light was Rodolph at the front of Santa's sleigh.
Chocolate covered cherries
Baby doll clothes made by Mom in secret.
Dr Dentons from Aunt Helen
The thing that I remember the most is getting up before the sun to go to Mass.  And no peeking to see if Santa had come.

I received that electric football game that I had been dreaming about. Later that day I was in the bathroom and heard what sounded like the hair clippers. I was so depressed, I thought Dad decided Christmas would be a good day to cut my hair. Instead he had got out the football game, what a relief!
I remember examining the Christmas ornaments on Uncle Jim's tree several times throughout the day in the hopes that there was still more candy hidden inside of them.
I remember our first Christmas here. Everything was so pretty with the lights and the snow! My parents drove us around to see all the lights. It was cold but we were still very excited!
I remember Madeline and I, on the day before Christmas, going to the golf course for sledding. I think Pat Gary and maybe the Wiley girls were involved too. We were hoping to make the time go faster.

I remember the Christmas I got an electric train set. I can still remember the smell of the transformer that operated the train. I also remember it had two rails, not three as some model trains do. I liked that. It was more realistic.

When I was a kid, we drove from Los Angeles to Mexico City (3-days) to spend the holidays with my mom's family. My mom has 11 siblings, so my grandmother's house was full of people talking, laughing, and kids screaming. There were too many of us, we never did presents, no one was organized or patient enough to set up a gift exchange, but there was plenty of food, baked goods, ponche, atole, and champurrado to go around.

In the states, I would get presents from Santa, but in Mexico, my parents would tell me we were too far away for Santa to bring me my present. In Mexico, kids get presents from the 3 wise men on Jan 6. 

A couple of times, I missed out on the presents altogether since Santa didn't go to Mexico, and we returned to the states before the three wise men would show up. That was O.K though I never really noticed. I was too busy running around the neighborhood with my cousins, lighting fireworks, buying sweets, and breaking pinatas at posadas.

My first Christmas with Bill was just 3 months after we had met.  I had been working at a county school for students with severe disabilities at the time.  A few days before Christmas, two of my students came for an overnight.  Renee and Christine were already over 18, and allowed by their parents to come.  Our plan was to practice meal preparation and to give the girls a life experience away from home.  Bill offered to come over and help out, so, with Bill wielding the saw, we chopped down our own Christmas tree and brought it home.  Then Bill offered to read to the girls, neither of whom could read.  I was preparing some snacks in the kitchen when I heard Renee and Christine whooping with laughter.  What was up???  They finally stopped laughing enough to tell me about Bill's unusual way of reading.  He looks at the book!!!  It seems that when teachers read to them, they faced the book forward and more or less recited the simple text.  When Renee or Christine read, they had no need to look at the book, as they were doing pretend reading.  Poor Bill appeared to these dear girls to be strangely handicapped by his need to look at the words in between showing them the pictures.  Bill joined in their laughter at himself whole-heartedly, just one more sign that he was the man for me.

fields.text: When the little drummer boy played for the baby Jesus, who or what kept time?
In the gospel of Luke, what is the first word the angel Gabriel speaks to Mary when telling her she would be the mother of Jesus?
fields.explanation: Some translations render the full line as "Hail, full of grace, the Lord is with you." and is the source of the first part of the Hail Mary.

fields.text: In "How the Grinch Stole Christmas" what is the name of the Grinch's dog?
Which of the following was the first holiday song played from space?
fields.explanation: It was played by the crew of the Gemini 6A flight in 1965, Wally Schirra and Thomas Stafford.

fields.text: Christmas was once banned in Boston. When would that be?
fields.explanation: From 1659 to 1681 there was a steep fine of 5 schillings for violations.

fields.text: The practice of hanging Christmas stockings is said to go back to...
In the song "O Christmas Tree," what about the tree is said to be so lovely?
fields.explanation: Because they are green both Summer and Winter, a sign of everlasting life.

fields.text: In the made-for-tv Christmas movie "The Homecoming," who played the part of Olivia Walton, the kids' mother?
fields.explanation: Michael Learned played that part in the subsequent TV series "The Waltons."

fields.text: When was Christmas named a federal holiday in the United States?
In Charles Dickens' "A Christmas Carol" who says "God bless us everyone."
When and by whom was December 25 selected as the date of Christmas?
fields.explanation: He set it during an existing Winter Solstice celebration

fields.text: St. Joseph is mentioned by name in all of the canonical gospels except for one. Which one does not mention Joseph by name?
fields.explanation: People in the gospel of Mark do, however, refer to Jesus as the "son of the carpenter."

Of Santa's nine reindeer, how many have five letters in their name?
fields.explanation: Vixen, Comet and Cupid all have five letters in their name.

fields.text: When "Miracle on 34th Street" was first promoted by the studio, they didn't want to emphasize its Christmas theme. Why?
In the song "The Twelve Days of Christmas" if my true love really did give me all the things mentioned on each day, what is the total number of french hens I would be given?
fields.explanation: Three french hens given every day from the third to the twelfth day, which is ten days for a total of 30 french hens.

fields.text: "For unto us a child is born, unto us a son is given, ... and the government shall be upon his shoulders... and his name shall be called Wonderful, Counselor, the Mighty God, the Everlasting Father, the Prince of Peace." These words from Handel's Messiah are base on a text from which book of the Bible?
fields.explanation: Isaiah 9:6, in the King James Version, I found it at Isaiah 9:6 in the New American Bible.

What is the most popular food for Christmas in Japan?
The actor who voiced the Grinch in "How the Grinch Stole Christmas" also starred in Hollywood movies as which of the following monsters?
fields.explanation: Boris Karloff was the voice of both the narrator and the Grinch.

In the 1942 movie "Holiday Inn" in which state is Holiday Inn located?
"Silent Night" was originally written for which of the following instruments:

fields.explanation: He was reflecting on the Christmas of 1986.

fields.correct_description: This is what's left of the speaker from an old-time radio. The coil of wire acted as an electromagnet that vibrated the paper cone in step with the incoming sound signal. I'm pretty sure I had permission to take it apart.
This is an old style soldering iron. One would heat up the end in a flame and then use it to solder items together. (Hmm... was Brian looking over my shoulder?)
This is an electric motor meant to turn the spit on a barbecue grill. Some of you may remember seeing this in use! (Yes, they did! This one was too easy!)

This is the connector to the picture tube in an old black and white TV set. I'm guessing but I think two of the wires were used to heat the filament which released electrons, two others to accelerate the electrons in a beam toward the screen, and one acting as a control of the brightness of the spot as it scanned horizontally and vertically.
This is an insulator from a knob and tube electrical system. This is one of the knobs. Electricians used these to route the wires in a house to where they wanted them.

fields.description: This is the spool box complete with thread of a hand cranked sewing machine.
An original Singer thread spool

This is part of an old-time automated fishing machine. The bait would trail off the back of the boat and when it sensed a tug on the line it would automatically reel in the hoped-for catch. This is only the reel, the motor and the sensing apparatus is not shown.

That's a solenoid from an old washing machine. When "on" the current running through the coil creates a magnetic field that drives a metal rod (not pictured). This is used to control flow of water into the machine.
Spool of copper wire

This is one end of a broken handle from an old water-well drill. The part broken off included a hub with a square hole that fit the end of drill-bit sections that would be turned to drill into the ground. As each drill section got low enough, they would add another and attach this handle to each new section to drill deeper in hopes of finding water.
This is a type of chisel called a gouge that is used in woodworking.
This is an old soldering iron. You would heat the metal (probably copper) end in a flame until it was hot enough to melt the solder.
This is a heavy duty fireplace poker
This is a barbecue grill motor for a rotisserie grill.
This is an electric motor for a rotisserie barbecue grill. It's hard to see in this photo, but the round spot in the upper middle is the hole for the spit.
It's a wiring harness for a rear taillight. I think a Ford between 1963 and 1967.

This is what's left of an old speaker-phone set up. The green portion rested under the old rotary-style phone and picked up the signal while the wires went variously to a microphone, amplifier and speaker intended to be placed on an office desk next to the phone.

fields.comment: The rules button wasn't working. Neither was the menu button that appears in the header on small screens. I've fixed them both but I discovered it because I was checking the rules to see if apostrophes or hyphenated words were allowed. The rules don't address the issue but the program itself doesn't allow for it so I think I'll just add it to the rules at least for now: no apostrophes or hyphenated words. Sorry.
Thank you,Jim.  I thought my iPad was just being mean to me.
Although, the word lists still don’t come up.

Oops! Looks like I missed another one! (...) There! Fixed! Everybody let me know if you find anything else on the website that is supposed to expand when you click it but doesn't. (What happened was that the "Bootstrap" software that I use made a small change in how it is done.)
I’d like to buy an “e”
e-caroling? What will they think of next!
Welcome to the game, Madeline.  Catch me if you can! 😏

Sorry folks! I just came up with another rule: no proper names (not even Jim!) The problem is, although I know names like Steve and Bart, I don't know all the names there may be and, when you come right down to it, just about anything could be considered a name.

Just so you know, I was leaning the other way on this one since it wasn't included in the rules before, though it will be real soon now. I didn't want to start putting proper names into the game's dictionary and probably have to take them out next year.
Janet...you are my acknowledged queen of words.  I serve at your feet!
No worries, Jim.  I figured proper names weren’t allowed, but sometimes proper names are common words too.
I do try to not make you work too hard looking up rejected words.
Thanks, Janet! It does take a while. And if I recognize a proper name as a common word, I will include it.
Madeline, (and everyone else): remember that you can come back later and add more words as you think of them.
No wonder the ents don’t talk to us anymore.  Orc makes it to the dictionary, but not ent!!
It's only because the orcs chose a name that matches the word for the killer whale. I guess they always idolized it.
What?  Is orca just a really big orc that swims in the water?
Hmmm...
Or perhaps just the plural of orc
Oh, thank heavens - no esses
Just 3 more words, Anne 😵‍💫
I doubt I get there unless some of my "not in dictionary" words make it through haha
And I've got a lot of catching up to do on those "not in dictionary" words!

There! I think I've checked all the words for Festive and Celebration. I did them just to be able to say the first two words were finalized. Now I start over at the beginning of the alphabet! (By the way, if you saw my name appearing in the scores for a little while, it's because I tried to add this comment in the word entry box above. Oops!)
Oh, oh, Anne.  It looks like you found some words that I haven’t found yet.  Now I have to stare at the chimney again.
I found words I didn't even know were words! I don't actually know what I'm spelling sometimes!
Found it (I think) - only 14 rejected words later.  Sorry Jim
Rather late to the game, Brian.  And what word do you have that I don’t have?
I don't know - all of our scores jumped when Jim added some words to the dictionary.
Is it just me or does the system not like plurals?
I think that it only likes plurals if they have already been added to the dictionary by Jim
That's right. The dictionary I got online only had singular forms of words so I have to keep adding the plurals.
Hmm... Somebody tried "you" and it should have been rejected because "generosity" doesn't have a "u" in it. It got through, somehow, but I didn't let it score. Sorry!

Jacob said I should protest the rejection of "Yavin." The internet tells me that Yavin is a fictional planet in the Star Wars galaxy. It first appeared in the 1977 film Star Wars and is depicted as a large red gas giant with an extensive satellite system of moons. I would have never thought of the word on my own haha.
Tell Jacob to read the rules - no proper names unless they're also used in some other manner as an adjective or verb.
I also protest the rejection of Yavin. Although I wasn't positive that was the correct spelling...
Maybe we could get a petition going
Wow, Brian!  You found a treasure trove of words.
Looks like Jim's been busy. Still no Yavin though.
What else could he possibly be doing?
So you figured out my word, now I have to figure out yours.  Don’ think there’s enough time.
Guess I should have tried ain, but I dismissed it as a foreign word.  Sigh.
I did have to think about it for a while, but it was in my English dictionary. I never thought "tantivy" would make it though but, there it was!
Wow! I just had 15 not-in-the-dictionary words to check and approved almost all of them! That's unusual!

I just added a page where you can see the scores for each past day of the game as Janet suggested. There is now a button under the Cumulative Scores table on the Scoreboard Page that will get you there. I guess I should an easy way to go back too.
There, two buttons added to the bottom of the Daily Scores page.
That’s the elmiest tree in the forest?  There must be an elmier one somewhere.
Definitely going to start working that word into my conversations. 😃

Yeah, I learned that a lot of things were words that I never thought were words. Who knew that "tantivy" was a "fast and furious gallop," or that an "ort" was a "small scrap or leaving of food after a meal is completed?" I accidentally let the word "ain't" sneak by. I was so surprised to find it in the dictionary I forgot the rule about no apostrophes. (I'll take it back out of the dictionary for next year though.)
There, I just finished checking the last set of words. The scores can now be considered final. I hope you all had fun!
I appreciate all the work that you put into this.  Thank you.

Is there a way to add a third box to the first page of words that would show the finalized words rejected.  And maybe have that 3rd box show up on everyone’s page.  Would that reduce your time checking words?

Hmm... do you mean the page where you first enter the words? I wouldn't want to let every one know the rejected words before they entered one -- might give hints. I could list them in red once a person enters them and they wouldn't appear in my list of words to check any more.
The "Games Played" number isn't always accurate. You can ignore it until I figure out why.

Janet reported a problem when playing the game on her tablet. When it came time to enter the solution no keyboard appeared to let her do that. It's probably the same on cell phones. I am studying the problem but no clues yet.
No problems on my laptop. I solved the puzzle and got a score of 580. Where do I pick up my prize teddy bear?
I couldn't pull up the keyboard on my phone, so I tried to use my Chromebook and wasn't able to enter my guess
Puzzle 2 worked. After I failed the first time...

Yes. The problem turns out to be a "known issue" with the software I'm using. I added an experimental fix but found the same thing with my android tablet: I could enter letters but not submit my answer. I'm working on building my own keyboard but that will probably take too long.
It should be working on tablets and cell phones now. The game now has its own (limited) keyboard. On a computer you can still type in your solution.
Worked for me.  My score was 560.  It would have been higher except I didn’t notice that the keyboard was “special”
Yes, it has everything you want and everything you need... and little else!
Brian's Teddy Bear will be delivered as soon as I can get the Transporter working.
